Sure! Here's an example code for a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 with one command, `ban`, implemented as a slash command:

```javascript
const Discord = require('discord.js');
const client = new Discord.Client();

const prefix = '/';

client.on('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}`);
});

client.on('message', async (message) => {
  if (message.author.bot) return;

  // Check if the message starts with a slash command prefix
  if (message.content.startsWith(prefix)) {
    const args = message.content.slice(prefix.length).trim().split(' ');
    const command = args.shift().toLowerCase();

    if (command === 'ban') {
      // Execute the ban command
      const target = message.mentions.users.first();
      if (!target) {
        const member = await message.guild.members.fetch(args[0]);
        if (!member) {
          return message.reply('Invalid user or member mentioned.');
        }
        await member.ban();
        return message.reply('User/member banned successfully.');
      } else {
        return message.reply('You can only ban users mentioned in the message.');
      }
    }
  }
});

client.login('YOUR_BOT_TOKEN');
```

Make sure you replace `'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN'` with your actual bot token.

This code sets up a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 and listens for messages. When a slash command (`/`) starts the message, it extracts the command name (`ban` in this case) and executes it. The bot checks if the mentioned user exists or if the mentioned member exists in the guild, then proceeds to ban the user or member accordingly.

Remember to create a new bot account on the Discord Developer Portal and obtain a bot token. Then, replace `'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN'` in the code with your actual bot token.

